            <h1>Fundamental Duties in the Indian Constitution</h1>
            <p>The Fundamental Duties are moral obligations enshrined in the Constitution to promote patriotism and uphold India's unity.</p>
        </header>

        <section>
            <h2>Introduction to Fundamental Duties</h2>
            <p>The Fundamental Duties were added by the <strong>42nd Amendment Act of 1976</strong> under Article 51A in Part IV-A. Initially comprising ten duties, they aim to inspire responsible citizenship.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>List of Fundamental Duties</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>To abide by the Constitution and respect the National Flag and National Anthem.</li>
                <li>To cherish and follow the noble ideals of India's freedom struggle.</li>
                <li>To uphold and protect the sovereignty, unity, and integrity of India.</li>
                <li>To defend the country and render national service when called upon.</li>
                <li>To promote harmony and common brotherhood, transcending all forms of diversity.</li>
                <li>To value and preserve the rich heritage of Indiaâ€™s composite culture.</li>
                <li>To protect the natural environment and have compassion for all living creatures.</li>
                <li>To develop scientific temper, humanism, and a spirit of inquiry and reform.</li>
                <li>To safeguard public property and to abjure violence.</li>
                <li>To strive for excellence in all endeavors to raise the nation to higher levels.</li>
                <li>To provide educational opportunities for children aged 6-14 years (added by the <strong>86th Amendment</strong>).</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Significance of Fundamental Duties</h2>
            <p>Fundamental Duties serve as reminders to citizens of their role in fostering national unity, social cohesion, and civic responsibility. They complement Fundamental Rights, ensuring a balanced approach to nation-building.</p>
